# Phase 1 Todo App Requirements Specification

## Functional Requirements

### 1. Basic Essentials

#### 1.1 Add Todo Item
- Command: `add "task title" "optional description"`
- Stores new todo item with unique ID in memory
- Sets initial status to "pending"
- Validates that task title is not empty
- Sets default priority to "medium" if not specified
- Creates empty tags list if not specified

#### 1.2 List Todo Items
- Command: `list`
- Displays all todo items with ID, status, title, description, priority, and tags
- Shows completed and pending items separately
- Formats output in a readable table

#### 1.3 Update Todo Item
- Command: `update <id> "new title" "optional new description"`
- Modifies existing todo item's title and/or description
- Validates that ID exists
- Shows confirmation message

#### 1.4 Complete Todo Item
- Command: `complete <id>`
- Updates status of specified todo item to "completed"
- Validates that ID exists and is not already completed
- Shows confirmation message

#### 1.5 Delete Todo Item
- Command: `delete <id>`
- Removes specified todo item from in-memory storage
- Validates that ID exists
- Shows confirmation message

### 2. Intermediate Organization

#### 2.1 Priorities & Tags
- Command: `priority <id> <high|medium|low>`
- Sets priority level for a specific todo item (High/Medium/Low)
- Command: `tag <id> <tag1> [tag2] [tag3]...`
- Adds tags to a specific todo item (Work/Home/Personal or custom tags)
- Command: `view <id>` to view detailed information about a specific todo
- Displays all details including priority and tags

#### 2.2 Search & Filter
- Command: `search <keyword>`
- Searches for todos containing the keyword in title or description
- Command: `filter <status|priority> <value>`
- Filters todos by status (pending/completed) or priority (high/medium/low)
- Command: `filter tag <tag>`
- Filters todos by specific tag

#### 2.3 Sort Tasks
- Command: `sort <priority|id>`
- Sorts todos by priority (high to low) or by ID (ascending)
- Default sort order is by ID ascending

## Non-Functional Requirements

### 1. Data Storage
- Store todos in-memory using Python list/dictionary
- No file persistence (volatile storage)
- Data resets on application restart
- Fast in-memory operations

### 2. Error Handling
- Validate all user inputs
- Handle invalid IDs gracefully
- Display meaningful error messages

### 3. Usability
- Provide clear command usage instructions
- Show helpful error messages
- Support standard CLI conventions